revision.text:
{{混同|神崎荘}}
'''Kanzaki-shō''' (神埼荘) was a shōen (manorial estate) in {{ill|Hizen Province|ja|肥前国|12=draft|12=draft}} during the {{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft|12=draft}} through the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was also known as Kanzaki-shō. The estate was historically part of the imperial domain.

== Overview ==

=== Location ===
It is believed to have been located in {{ill|Kanzaki District, Hizen Province|ja|神埼郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, corresponding to present-day {{ill|Kanzaki, Saga|ja|神埼市|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Saga Prefecture|ja|佐賀県|12=draft|12=draft}}.

=== Size ===
As of {{ill|Shōō (era)|ja|正応|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (1291), it covered approximately 3,000 chō.

=== Origins ===
The estate originated as a {{ill|Chokushiden|ja|勅旨田|12=draft|12=draft}} comprising 690 chō established in {{ill|Jōwa (Heian period)|ja|承和|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (836). By {{ill|Chōwa (Heian period)|ja|長和|12=draft|12=draft}} 4 (1015), it had been formalized as a shōen and passed down as an imperial domain.

=== Lords ===
The estate was part of the imperial domain (held by emperors such as {{ill|Emperor Go-Shirakawa|ja|後白河法皇|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Emperor Go-Toba|ja|後鳥羽上皇|12=draft|12=draft}}), transferred to the {{ill|Miura clan|ja|三浦氏|12=draft|12=draft}} (e.g., {{ill|Miura Yasumura|ja|三浦泰村|12=draft|12=draft}}), and then returned to the imperial domain under figures like {{ill|Emperor Go-Saga|ja|後嵯峨上皇|12=draft|12=draft}}.

=== History and Decline ===
After its development as a chokushiden in the 9th century, the estate's management involved local families such as the {{ill|Shikaji clan|ja|鹿路氏|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Hirotaki clan|ja|廣滝氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. Members of the central aristocracy, such as branches of the {{ill|Fujiwara clan|ja|藤原氏|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Taira clan|ja|平氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, also settled in the area. These included the {{ill|Mise clan|ja|三瀬氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, who were Fujiwara descendants.

During the {{ill|Taira clan government|ja|平氏政権|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kanzaki-shō became a hub for {{ill|Japan-Song Dynasty trade|ja|日宋貿易|12=draft|12=draft}} alongside {{ill|Dazaifu|ja|大宰府|12=draft|12=draft}} and Satsuma Ata. It was controlled by the family of {{ill|Taira no Tadamori|ja|平忠盛|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Following the {{ill|Tōi invasion|ja|刀伊の入寇|12=draft|12=draft}} in the 11th-12th centuries, a branch of the {{ill|Chinzei Taira clan|ja|鎮西平氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, represented by {{ill|Taira no Kanesuke|ja|平兼輔|12=draft|12=draft}} (later {{ill|Kanzaki Kanesuke|ja|神埼兼輔|12=draft|12=draft}}), settled in Kanzaki-shō. It is said that Kanesuke's lineage became the {{ill|Kanzaki clan|ja|神埼氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, claiming descent from {{ill|Taira no Sukemoto|ja|平季基|1=Taira no Suemoto|12=draft|12=draft}}, who was involved in the development of Shimazu-shō.

In {{ill|Nin'an|ja|仁安|12=draft|12=draft}} 3 (1168), {{ill|Minamoto no Mitsusue|ja|源満末|12=draft|12=draft}}, a descendant of the {{ill|Saga Genji|ja|嵯峨源氏|12=draft|12=draft}} branch of the {{ill|Minamoto clan|ja|源氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, was appointed shōkan (estate administrator). Mitsusue's descendants later became jitō (estate stewards) in the {{ill|Chikugo Province|ja|筑後国|12=draft|12=draft}} and founded the {{ill|Kamachi clan|ja|蒲池氏|12=draft|12=draft}}. Around this time, {{ill|Mount Sefuri's Thousand Temples|ja|脊振千坊|12=draft|12=draft}} flourished, as evidenced by sites like the ruins of {{ill|Reisen-ji|ja|霊仙寺跡|12=draft|12=draft}}.

During the {{ill|Mongol invasions of Japan|ja|元寇|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kanzaki-shō was divided as reward lands, with families like the {{ill|Kōno clan|ja|河野氏|12=draft|12=draft}} (descendants of the {{ill|Ōyamazumi Shrine|ja|大山祇神社|1=Ōyamazumi Shrine|12=draft|12=draft}} lineage) receiving portions.

By the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the estate had lost its function as a shōen, surviving only in name.

In the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Ryūzōji clan|ja|龍造寺氏|12=draft|12=draft}} rose to prominence in Hizen Province. Following their defeat in the {{ill|Battle of Kawakami Gorge|ja|川上峡合戦|12=draft|12=draft}}, the power of Mount Sefuri's temples faded from the historical stage (see {{ill|Jindai Katsutoshi|ja|神代勝利|12=draft|12=draft}}).

== References ==
* {{Cite book|和書|title=国史大辞典|publisher={{ill|Yoshikawa Kōbunkan|ja|吉川弘文館|12=draft|12=draft}}}}
* {{Cite book|和書|title=日本史広辞典|publisher={{ill|Yamakawa Shuppansha|ja|山川出版社|12=draft|12=draft}}}}

== See Also ==
* {{ill|Japan-Song Dynasty trade|ja|日宋貿易|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Insei|ja|院政|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Taira clan government|ja|平氏政権|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Minamoto no Mitsusue|ja|源満末|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|List of shōen in Japan|ja|日本の荘園の一覧|12=draft|12=draft}}



